{{short description|A cold water current in the Sea of Japan that flows southward from near Vladivostok along the coast of the Korean Peninsula}}
The '''North Korea Cold Current''' (NKCC) is a cold water oceanic current in the [[Sea of Japan]] (East Sea of Korea) that flows southward from near [[Vladivostok]] along the coastline of the eastern [[Korean Peninsula]]. It is a branch of the [[Liman Current]] from the [[Sea of Okhotsk]] and has a flow rate of about a half knot. The NKCC meets the northward flowing [[East Korean Warm Current]] at latitude 37–38°&nbsp;N, causing the flow to separate from the peninsula.<ref name=brink_robinson2005/> At about latitude 40°&nbsp;N, the NKCC meets the [[Tsushima Warm Current]].<ref name=osj44_1_43/>

