[[File:Geysir01.jpg|thumb|Summer near [[Geysir]], [[Iceland]].]]
In [[Norse mythology]], '''Sumarr''' ([[Old Norse]] "Summer"<ref name=ORCHARD154>Orchard (1997:154).</ref>) and '''Vetr''' (Old Norse "Winter"<ref name=ORCHARD174>Orchard (1997:174).</ref>) are personified [[season]]s. Sumarr and Vetr, personified, are attested in the ''[[Poetic Edda]]'', compiled in the 13th century from earlier traditional sources, and the ''[[Prose Edda]]'', written in the 13th century by [[Snorri Sturluson]]. In both, the two are given genealogies, while in the ''Prose Edda'' the two figure into a number of [[kenning]]s used by various [[skald]]s.

==Attestations==
[[File:Vinter.jpg|thumb|Winter in [[Blefjell, Norway]].]]
===''Poetic Edda''===
In the stanza 26 of the  ''Poetic Edda'' poem ''[[Vafþrúðnismál]]'', the god [[Odin]] (disguised as "[[List of names of Odin|Gagnráðr]]") asks the [[jötunn]] [[Vafþrúðnir]]  from where warm Sumarr and Vetr come from, stating that they arrived "first among the Wise powers".<ref name=LARRINGTON44>Larrington (1996:44).</ref> In stanza 27, Vafþrúðnir responds:
<blockquote>
:Wind-cool [Vindsvalr] he is called, Winter's [Vetr's] father,
:and Mild-One [Svásuðr], the father of Summer [Sumarr].<ref name=LARRINGTON44/>
</blockquote>
The second half of this stanza is missing from early manuscripts, but some later manuscripts feature the addition of:
<blockquote>
:And both of these shall ever be
:Till the gods to destruction go.<ref name=BELLOWS75>Bellows (1936:75).</ref>
</blockquote>

===''Prose Edda''===
In chapter 19 of the ''Prose Edda'' book ''[[Gylfaginning]]'', [[Gylfi|Gangleri]] (king [[Gylfi]] in disguise) asks why there's an evident difference between summer and winter. The enthroned figure of High responds, and (after scolding him for asking a question everyone knows the answer to) states that the father of Sumarr is Svásuðr, who is quite pleasant, while the father of Vetr is referred to as Vindsvalr or, alternately, Vindljóni, and that Vetr derives his countenance from his ancestors, as they are "cruel and cold-hearted kinsmen".<ref name=BYOCK30>Byock (2005:30).</ref>

Sumarr and Vetr are additionally personified in the ''Prose Edda'' book ''[[Skáldskaparmál]]'', where they are referred to in [[kenning]]s. Kennings for Sumarr are given in chapter 30, including "son of Svásuðr", "comfort of the snakes", "growth of men", exemplified in an excerpt given from a work by the [[skald]] [[Egill Skallagrímsson]] where "Valley-fish's mercy" points to "Snake's mercy", which signifies "Summer".<ref name=FAULKES94>Faulkes (1995:94).</ref> Kennings are given for Vetr in chapter 26; "Son of Vindsvalr", "snake's death", and "storm season". Excerpts of works by the skalds [[Ormr Steinþórsson]] (who uses the kenning "Vindsvalr's son") and Ásgrímr (who employs the kenning "snake woe") are then given as examples.<ref name=FAULKES93>Faulkes (1995:93).</ref> Both Sumarr and Vetr are given as terms for "times" in chapter 63.<ref name=FAULKES144>Faulkes (1995:144).</ref>

